    </exercisegroup>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p> Suppoe <m>B=\{\boldv_1,\boldv_2,\boldv_3\}</m> be a basis for the vector space<m>V</m>.
        Let <m>B'=\{\boldu_1,\boldu_2,\boldu_3\}</m>, where <me>
          \boldu_1 = \boldv_1, \boldu_2 = \boldv_1 + \boldv_2, \boldu_3 = \boldv_1 +\boldv_2 +
        \boldv_3
        </me>.
        Prove that <m>B'</m> is a basis. </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p> First explain why it is enough to show that <m>B'</m> is linearly independent. </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <title>Two-dimensional subspaces of <m>\R^3</m></title>
    <statement>
      <p> Prove that the 2-dimensional subspaces of <m>\R^3</m> are precisely the planes
        that pass through the origin. In other words, show (a) that any plane <m>
        \mathcal{P}\subseteq\R^3</m> passing through the origin is a 2-dimensional subspace, and
        conversely, (b) that any 2-dimensional subspace <m>W\subseteq \R^3</m> is a plane passing
        through the origin. </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p> For (b), begin with a basis of <m>B=\{(a,b,c), (d,e,f)\}</m> of <m>W</m>, and use the
        cross product to find a normal vector <m>\boldn</m> that defines <m>W</m> as a plane. </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p> Let <m>V=M_{33}</m>, <m>W=\{A\in M_{33}\colon A^T=-A\}</m>, and <m>W'=\Span\{ A_1, A_2,
        A_3\}</m>, where <me>
          A_1=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 1\amp 2\\ -1\amp 0\amp 1\\ -2\amp -1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix} , \
        A_2=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 1\amp -1\\ -1\amp 0\amp 1\\ 1\amp -1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix} ,\
        A_3=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 1\amp 0\\ -1\amp 0\amp -1\\ 0\amp 1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        Show that <m>W'=W</m> as follows: <ol>
          <li> Show that <m>W'\subseteq W</m>. </li>
          <li>
            <p> Compute the dimensions of <m>W'</m> and <m>W</m> and use <xref
                ref="cor_dimension_subspace" />. </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p> Let <m>V=M_{23}</m> and define <me>
          W=\{A\in M_{23}\colon \text{ all rows and columns of \(A\) sum to 0 } \}
        </me>.
        Find a basis for <m>W</m> by inspection and compute its dimension. </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise xml:id="ex_dimension_matrix_families">
    <title>Dimensions of important matrix subspaces</title>
    <statement>
      <p> Let <m>V=M_{nn}</m>. Compute <m>\dim W</m> for each subspace <m>W\subset M_{nn}</m>. </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <title>Upper triangular matrices</title>
          <p>
            <m>W=\{A\in M_{nn}\colon A \text{ is upper triangular}\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Symmetric matrices</title>
          <p>
            <m>W=\{A\in M_{nn}\colon A^T=A\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Skew-symmetric matrices</title>
          <p>
            <m>W=\{A\in M_{nn}\colon A^T=-A\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p> Use your results from <xref ref="ex_basis_matrix_families" />. The identity <me>
        \sum_{i=1}^n i=\frac{(n+1)n}{2}
        </me> will be helpful. </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p> Let <m>A\in M_{nn}</m>. Show that there is a nonzero polynomial <m>p(x)=a_{n^2}x^{n^2}+a_{n^2-1}x^{n^2-1}+\cdots
        +a_1x+a_0</m> such that <me>
          p(A)=a_{n^2}A^{n^2}+a_{n^2-1}A^{n^2-1}+\cdots +a_1A+a_0I_n=\underset{n\times n}{\boldzero}
        </me>
        .
    </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p> Consider the set <m>S=\{A^{n^2}, A^{n^2-1}, \dots, A, I\}\subseteq M_{nn}</m> and use a
        relevant statement from <xref ref="th_dimension_compendium" />. Treat two cases separately:
        (a) the powers of <m>A</m> are all distinct; (b) <m>A^i=A^j</m> for some <m>0\leq i &lt;
        j\leq n^2</m>. </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>
